WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.838
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.784 --> 00:00:07.450
JESSE HAINES: First
of all, I'm actually

00:00:07.450 --> 00:00:13.660
just curious to know how many
of you here in this audience

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:17.380
were either born outside
the United States,

00:00:17.380 --> 00:00:20.730
or have a parent that was born
outside the United States?

00:00:20.730 --> 00:00:23.030
Just to get a show of hands.

00:00:23.030 --> 00:00:23.530
All right.

00:00:23.530 --> 00:00:26.560
I'd say that's
almost half the room.

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:28.720
Interesting.

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:31.255
OK, so just giving you a
sense of your audience.

00:00:31.255 --> 00:00:33.880
MARY SKAFIDAS: That's great.

00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:38.560
JESSE HAINES: So tell us a
little bit about where you came

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:43.270
up with the idea for this
book, which is, again,

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:49.210
72 essays all about immigration,
from folks that you've heard

00:00:49.210 --> 00:00:51.410
of and others that you haven't.

00:00:51.410 --> 00:00:53.574
But like, why?

00:00:53.574 --> 00:00:55.990
ANDREW TISCH: Well, I had
joined the board of the New York

00:00:55.990 --> 00:00:57.884
Historical Society.

00:00:57.884 --> 00:01:00.550
And one of the things we have at
the New York Historical Society

00:01:00.550 --> 00:01:03.670
is a very nice auditorium
that we loan out

00:01:03.670 --> 00:01:07.510
periodically to the immigration
and Naturalization Service.

00:01:07.510 --> 00:01:10.960
So I was asked if I
would offer greetings

00:01:10.960 --> 00:01:13.540
to 100 new immigrants
who were being

00:01:13.540 --> 00:01:17.050
sworn in on behalf of NYHS.

00:01:17.050 --> 00:01:18.580
I said, sure, why not?

00:01:18.580 --> 00:01:21.280
And as I was
preparing my remarks,

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:24.940
I decided to talk about how my
family got here-- the family

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:29.020
lore of how we came to America.

00:01:29.020 --> 00:01:33.010
And as I was sitting there
looking out on the audience,

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:36.235
I thought to myself,
everyone has a story.

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:42.250
Virtually every one
of us is an immigrant.

00:01:42.250 --> 00:01:45.520
And with everything
that's going on--

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:49.370
and this was now 18 months
ago, 24 months ago--

00:01:49.370 --> 00:01:52.390
with everything that was
going on then, I said,

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:55.240
why not start to tell
some of the stories?

00:01:55.240 --> 00:02:00.040
And so I went back to the
office and talked to Mary.

00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:03.550
And Mary and I had been
writing for several years,

00:02:03.550 --> 00:02:05.470
writing op-eds together.

00:02:05.470 --> 00:02:08.037
And I said to her, how would
you like to write a book?

00:02:08.037 --> 00:02:09.370
You're not gonna make any money.

00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:16.040
MARY SKAFIDAS: I ran away
and hid under my desk.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:16.540
No.

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:23.890
I was very engaged, and
wanted to do this right

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:24.940
from when he said it.

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:29.740
We had a great time just
researching his family history.

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:32.279
And I was born here, but
I didn't speak English

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:34.570
till I was five years old
because my parents just spoke

00:02:34.570 --> 00:02:37.619
Greek, and still
just speak Greek.

00:02:37.619 --> 00:02:39.910
So it was something that was
near and dear to my heart.

00:02:39.910 --> 00:02:43.090
And you could see, when he
came back from the ceremony,

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:44.090
he was energized.

00:02:44.090 --> 00:02:45.650
It was like, we're
all immigrants.

00:02:45.650 --> 00:02:46.640
And it shouldn't be an epiphany.

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:47.560
We are all immigrants.

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:51.464
But it takes a moment like that
for you to really realize it.

00:02:51.464 --> 00:02:52.630
JESSE HAINES: And then what?

00:02:52.630 --> 00:02:54.730
You've got such an amazing
collection of stories

00:02:54.730 --> 00:02:57.850
here from everyone
from Marlo Thomas,

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:01.330
Nancy Pelosi, Rabbi Angela--

00:03:01.330 --> 00:03:02.890
like just such a mix.

00:03:02.890 --> 00:03:04.630
How did you find these people?

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:06.280
Were they reluctant to share?

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:07.690
Excited to [INAUDIBLE]?

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:09.940
ANDREW TISCH: Very few people
were reluctant to share.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:11.900
As a matter of fact,
when you talk to people,

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:14.680
they got energized by it.

00:03:14.680 --> 00:03:16.240
You know, many
people, after we asked

00:03:16.240 --> 00:03:18.040
them three or four
questions, would

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.440
start to come up with things
that they hadn't thought about.

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:22.990
And at the end of
the discussion,

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:24.580
they were thanking us.

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:30.060
But we started out by
interviewing people.

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:33.280
And we realized, or at least
I came to the realization,

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:36.610
I can't write in
another person's voice.

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:40.790
So maybe I was being a
little bit lazy, but I said,

00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:42.630
why don't you write an essay?

00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:47.140
Write 500 to 1,500 words
about how you or your family

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:48.100
got here.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:51.790
And then we'll do
a light edit on it.

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:55.390
And the stories
that we got in were

00:03:55.390 --> 00:03:59.260
unbelievable because it
was people really pouring

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:03.550
their hearts out about what
America meant to them, what

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:04.990
their family meant to them.

00:04:04.990 --> 00:04:08.150
It was the stories.

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:11.380
Each one of them tells a story.

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:15.840
And collecting the stories
was kind of the easy part,

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:17.870
because people wanted to.

00:04:17.870 --> 00:04:20.709
It was telling people, no, we
have enough stories already,

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:25.710
or no, we don't need
this story or that story.

00:04:25.710 --> 00:04:30.220
So getting people to
open up their hearts,

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:33.189
open up their minds,
write about it,

00:04:33.189 --> 00:04:34.480
that was kind of the easy part.

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:39.520
JESSE HAINES: What
were the common themes?

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:42.780
I know you categorized the
stories throughout the book.

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:45.320
You kind of grouped them.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:47.250
But tell us a little
bit about some

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:50.170
of the themes that emerged
as you started to look across

00:04:50.170 --> 00:04:54.040
all these fascinating tales.

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.280
MARY SKAFIDAS: Well,
overwhelmingly there's hope.

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:00.025
There's hope and courage,
and that comes across.

00:05:00.025 --> 00:05:01.900
Even though that there's
different chapters--

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:03.100
there is the fleers.

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:04.120
There's the lovers.

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:08.190
There is the survivors.

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:09.940
Even as you look
across from them,

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:12.990
they're leaving a place
for something better,

00:05:12.990 --> 00:05:15.014
and it takes a tremendous
amount of courage

00:05:15.014 --> 00:05:16.680
to be able to leave
everything you know,

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:20.100
even if it's not great,
and try to set up

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.890
a life in this new country.

00:05:22.890 --> 00:05:27.710
But I think we carve the
chapters up into themes,

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:33.180
but really, a lot of the
stories would fit in any chapter

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:35.340
because I think the
common theme of hope,

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.780
and bravery, and courage come
through in almost all of them.

00:05:38.780 --> 00:05:40.350
ANDREW TISCH: One
of the problems

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:44.190
we had early on was figuring out
how to divide up the chapters.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:46.782
So we thought about
doing it alphabetically.

00:05:46.782 --> 00:05:48.240
And then we realized,
well, we have

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:51.860
Alan Alda, and Arleen Alda,
and we have Ashok Amritraj,

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:53.060
and Ahmed Ahmed.

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:58.380
We had way too many AAs for 72,
so we couldn't do it that way.

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:00.690
We couldn't do it
geographically,

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:04.470
because you had Europe,
Africa, so you'd almost

00:06:04.470 --> 00:06:07.170
be doing it racially,
which we didn't want to do.

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:08.850
We couldn't do it
chronologically

00:06:08.850 --> 00:06:11.460
because we had people
from the Mayflower,

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:15.390
and people who came over--

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:20.420
we literally had one person
who wrote his essay on the day

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:24.840
that he was sworn
in as a US citizen.

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:27.950
And we decided to do it--

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:29.117
MARY SKAFIDAS: Thematically.

00:06:29.117 --> 00:06:30.325
ANDREW TISCH: --thematically.

00:06:30.325 --> 00:06:31.980
We had people who
were coming over here

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:34.620
for opportunity, people
who are coming over here

00:06:34.620 --> 00:06:38.610
for love, people who were coming
over here fleeing something.

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:43.620
But I guess the common theme
was that people came over here

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:47.730
for opportunity, and
because they really

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:53.400
believed that there were
things here that they couldn't

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:55.860
get anywhere else in the world.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:07:01.980
And I'll take the
example of my family, who

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:07.210
came from [? Dniprovska, ?]
which was in Ukraine.

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:10.706
And they could have just
as easily gone to Warsaw.

00:07:10.706 --> 00:07:12.330
It probably would
have been much easier

00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:18.030
to go to Warsaw, which had a
great Jewish community there

00:07:18.030 --> 00:07:22.200
in 1905, and it would have
been a very safe choice.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:23.950
And they would have
been wiped out.

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:27.630
And I would never have been
here after World War II.

00:07:27.630 --> 00:07:33.000
Somebody in my family,
probably my great grandfather,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.130
took a leap of faith,
heard that there

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:39.480
was something going on here
that was worth pursuing,

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:40.110
and came here.

00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:46.950
And six months later, brought
his wife and their three

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:49.020
children, one of whom
was my grandfather.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:51.450
JESSE HAINES: Amazing.

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:55.710
So, so powerful,
those crossroads.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:58.500
So who is this book for?

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:00.960
Who do you hope reads this book?

00:08:04.512 --> 00:08:06.470
MARY SKAFIDAS: Well, I
think we wanted to raise

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:08.330
awareness of the issue.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:11.060
And we wanted to do it in
a way that didn't alienate.

00:08:11.060 --> 00:08:14.030
I mean, right now there
are sides in immigration.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:16.560
We didn't want to
alienate either side.

00:08:16.560 --> 00:08:18.740
We really just wanted
to remind people

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:23.370
of what makes America great,
and that we're all immigrants.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:26.840
And I think we've been able to
accomplish that because we're

00:08:26.840 --> 00:08:30.110
telling the personal
story of success,

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:33.020
and it resonates with
everyone and with every group.

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:35.309
ANDREW TISCH: The book
is completely apolitical.

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:39.230
And we run the gamut from
Nancy Pelosi to Elaine Chao,

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:41.450
from Cory Booker to Tim Scott.

00:08:41.450 --> 00:08:46.280
We have people on the left
and people on the right.

00:08:46.280 --> 00:08:52.200
Immigration itself really
is not a political issue,

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:54.570
in most cases.

00:08:54.570 --> 00:08:56.660
There are a few
people for whom it is.

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:59.570
There are Native Americans
who have been here,

00:08:59.570 --> 00:09:03.580
and who have gotten
screwed, quite frankly.

00:09:03.580 --> 00:09:06.530
There are people who came
over here unwillingly, i.e.

00:09:06.530 --> 00:09:08.250
slaves.

00:09:08.250 --> 00:09:15.870
But for the most part, this
is not a political book.

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:19.310
This is a book to
raise awareness that we

00:09:19.310 --> 00:09:21.740
are a nation of immigrants.

00:09:21.740 --> 00:09:25.640
America and Israel are
probably the only countries

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:31.140
in the world that have been
created by and for immigrants.

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:31.890
JESSE HAINES: Yes.

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:33.270
Yes.

00:09:33.270 --> 00:09:35.760
It's not a political
book, but boy,

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:39.770
is immigration a hot
political topic right now.

00:09:39.770 --> 00:09:43.080
So I want to kind of delve
into that a little bit.

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:48.590
What do you think--

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:52.130
has the direction of
the political discourse

00:09:52.130 --> 00:09:53.720
around immigration--

00:09:56.390 --> 00:09:57.860
are we moving forward?

00:09:57.860 --> 00:10:00.110
Are we moving backwards?

00:10:00.110 --> 00:10:03.600
It is a hot topic.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:04.570
It is divisive.

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:13.180
What is our status as a
nation today, in terms of,

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:17.030
have we moved kind of backwards
or forwards in our ability

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:22.340
to talk about this
issue of immigration?

00:10:22.340 --> 00:10:25.820
ANDREW TISCH: Well, we've
always been somewhat xenophobic

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:28.310
in this country.

00:10:28.310 --> 00:10:30.410
Last year was the
100th anniversary

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:36.440
of the Immigration Act
of 1918, which was also

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:41.390
known as the Asiatic Barred
Act, which basically barred most

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:45.980
Asians from coming to America
because people in California

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:48.350
thought there were
too many Asians here.

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:52.700
And it was literally
impossible for an Asian woman

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:56.420
to get a visa to come
here because people wanted

00:10:56.420 --> 00:10:58.570
the Asians that came here--

00:10:58.570 --> 00:11:00.320
if they wanted to get
married-- to go back

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:03.920
to their native country
and get married, and not

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:05.120
stay in America.

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:07.910
So we we've always been
somewhat xenophobic.

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:16.820
We've always had negative
discourse about immigration.

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:18.920
When people first
started coming in,

00:11:18.920 --> 00:11:21.230
when groups first
started coming in,

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:26.000
it's taken a generation
and generation and a half

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.650
for them to be accepted.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:33.050
So it's not that this is
the first time that we've

00:11:33.050 --> 00:11:38.600
had terrible xenophobia.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:42.140
But what's going
on now is certainly

00:11:42.140 --> 00:11:45.470
of great concern
to every one of us.

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:48.050
MARY SKAFIDAS: In
pulling together

00:11:48.050 --> 00:11:51.050
the stories for the book,
we studied the waves

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:53.125
of immigration because
we wanted to make sure

00:11:53.125 --> 00:11:55.250
that we had enough stories
that were representative

00:11:55.250 --> 00:11:56.730
of each wave.

00:11:56.730 --> 00:12:00.650
And you know, we quickly
came to the realization

00:12:00.650 --> 00:12:03.350
that how we feel
about immigration

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:05.120
as a country is cyclical.

00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:06.620
And we happen to
be in a down cycle,

00:12:06.620 --> 00:12:11.000
but I think people realize
that the US absolutely

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.280
needs immigrants.

00:12:12.280 --> 00:12:13.650
Right?

00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:18.560
40% of Fortune 500 companies
were founded by immigrants,

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:19.367
or they were--

00:12:19.367 --> 00:12:21.200
ANDREW TISCH: Or the
children of immigrants.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:22.010
MARY SKAFIDAS: --the
children of immigrants.

00:12:22.010 --> 00:12:22.310
So--

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:23.690
JESSE HAINES: Including Google.

00:12:23.690 --> 00:12:24.260
ANDREW TISCH: Including Google.

00:12:24.260 --> 00:12:24.840
MARY SKAFIDAS: Right.

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:25.340
Right.

00:12:25.340 --> 00:12:26.360
Right.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.940
So I think every
new group that comes

00:12:28.940 --> 00:12:30.350
in, there's always this fear.

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:31.850
And it takes a while
to get over it.

00:12:31.850 --> 00:12:33.770
But then there's the realization
that you need immigrants.

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:34.610
We need immigrants.

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:35.000
JESSE HAINES: Yeah.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:36.710
Let's talk about that
a little bit more.

00:12:36.710 --> 00:12:38.126
I mean, from your
standpoint, what

00:12:38.126 --> 00:12:41.090
are some of the economic
arguments for immigration?

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:45.086
Because I think that
also fuels the fear

00:12:45.086 --> 00:12:49.130
of things being taken away.

00:12:49.130 --> 00:12:52.340
But there's a pretty
strong economic rationale

00:12:52.340 --> 00:12:53.670
for why immigration is--

00:12:53.670 --> 00:12:55.045
ANDREW TISCH:
Well, first of all,

00:12:55.045 --> 00:12:58.910
let's just take something
as simple as unemployment.

00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:00.770
We have basically
full employment

00:13:00.770 --> 00:13:02.880
in the United States right now.

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:10.260
We have 3.1%, 3.2% unemployment.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:14.660
That is full employment,
and anyone that wants a job

00:13:14.660 --> 00:13:15.950
can probably get a job.

00:13:15.950 --> 00:13:19.790
Maybe not the best job
in the world, but we

00:13:19.790 --> 00:13:23.960
need more people to be working.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:26.660
And we just don't
have enough people.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:31.250
Now, we have, in this
country, achieved ZPG, also.

00:13:31.250 --> 00:13:35.060
So if we want to change
the zero population growth,

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:37.690
that's going to take
about 20, 25 years.

00:13:37.690 --> 00:13:41.090
And we don't have the social
systems to run that many more

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:45.780
people through the schools,
so that's impractical.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:48.620
So we need immigrants.

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:50.340
We need immigrants to come in.

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:53.660
We also need immigrants because
we've got three Ponzi schemes

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:55.200
in Washington.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:58.065
We've got Medicare, Medicaid,
and Social Security.

00:13:58.065 --> 00:13:58.940
JESSE HAINES: Got it.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:13:59.616
Got it.

00:13:59.616 --> 00:14:01.490
ANDREW TISCH: And the
only way that they work

00:14:01.490 --> 00:14:07.940
is if we get a broader and
broader population working

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:13.490
base to pay in, because
the three of them

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:15.920
are funded by
current dollars, not

00:14:15.920 --> 00:14:18.590
by any kind of real trust fund.

00:14:18.590 --> 00:14:21.620
It's a game the government has
played, and everybody knows it,

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:24.950
and nobody's doing
anything about it.

00:14:24.950 --> 00:14:27.920
So we need immigration.

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:33.340
We need immigrants just
as workers, number one.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:39.360
Number two, many immigrants take
jobs that nobody else will do.

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:41.350
And it's a plain and
simple fact of life

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:44.380
that immigrants want to come
here and they want to work,

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:45.880
and they want to
work hard, and they

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:47.900
want to do whatever it takes.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:49.690
And oftentimes, they
end up with the jobs

00:14:49.690 --> 00:14:51.630
that nobody else will take.

00:14:54.190 --> 00:14:56.420
So that's very important.

00:14:56.420 --> 00:15:04.240
And then you look at the
brains that stay here,

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:08.250
and the number of
PhDs that come here.

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:10.120
And you look at the
university systems.

00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:13.570
We have the greatest
university system in the world.

00:15:13.570 --> 00:15:16.690
Of the top 50 universities
in the world, 40 of them

00:15:16.690 --> 00:15:21.970
are American universities
by the latest rankings.

00:15:21.970 --> 00:15:27.940
Boy, if I was running the
country, any foreigner that

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:33.280
got a PhD, I'd immediately
confiscate their passport,

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:34.600
and pull their--

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:36.550
and say, you got a PhD here.

00:15:36.550 --> 00:15:39.670
You got to work here
for X number of years.

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:43.913
Because to give them an
eviction notice is insanity.

00:15:43.913 --> 00:15:44.704
JESSE HAINES: Yeah.

00:15:51.470 --> 00:15:53.720
And I'm not asking where
you stand on these issues,

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:59.070
but why is immigration, at this
moment in time, so polarizing?

00:15:59.070 --> 00:16:05.190
Why are we involved
in such heated debate

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:08.210
over the wall, the ban.

00:16:08.210 --> 00:16:12.810
Given that it's hard
to argue with, I think,

00:16:12.810 --> 00:16:19.770
what this book makes so
clear, we are all immigrants.

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:30.100
This country is founded
on values of openness

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:35.140
and embracing everyone from
gathering our huddled masses.

00:16:37.750 --> 00:16:41.465
Why has the dialogue around
immigration gotten so heated?

00:16:41.465 --> 00:16:43.840
ANDREW TISCH: Well let me let
me turn around and ask you,

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:46.480
what are we not polarized on
in this country right now?

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:47.779
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:47.779 --> 00:16:48.570
JESSE HAINES: True.

00:16:48.570 --> 00:16:49.070
True.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.700
ANDREW TISCH: We are living
in a political environment

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:55.000
where everything
is being polarized.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:00.190
And that gets into a broader
question of leadership,

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:09.190
but I think it's going to take a
while for the pendulum to swing

00:17:09.190 --> 00:17:12.420
back to more cooperation.

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:15.220
A lot of the things
I'm doing in Washington

00:17:15.220 --> 00:17:19.660
involve trying to reestablish
some sort of decorum

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:24.454
and ability to work
across the aisles.

00:17:24.454 --> 00:17:25.579
JESSE HAINES: That's great.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:26.829
That's great.

00:17:26.829 --> 00:17:30.190
What changes would you make
in our current immigration

00:17:30.190 --> 00:17:35.220
policy, were you to be able
to wave your magic wand?

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:36.920
ANDREW TISCH: You
want to start that?

00:17:36.920 --> 00:17:39.430
MARY SKAFIDAS: Sure.

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:41.980
I think Andrew actually
outlined a number of them.

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:45.910
And obviously, we are not
immigration policy experts,

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:47.800
nor do we play
one on television.

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:53.200
And this is not a question that
we typically want to answer.

00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:57.250
I mean, the focus of this was
really to raise awareness.

00:17:57.250 --> 00:18:02.380
But I think the realization
that we need immigrants,

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:05.380
that we are pushing a
lot of the brain power

00:18:05.380 --> 00:18:10.480
that we educate out
of the country--

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:13.930
should it be based on skill?

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:17.230
Should it be based on family
members bringing more family

00:18:17.230 --> 00:18:18.160
members over?

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:20.620
I think those are
valid questions.

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:23.920
And if they could be done in a
way that wasn't so sensational

00:18:23.920 --> 00:18:26.950
and just on social
media only, I think

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:29.650
these are valid questions
that we should ask ourselves,

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:31.640
and would help the
country move forward.

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:35.320
ANDREW TISCH: And things
like DACA-- that's insanity.

00:18:35.320 --> 00:18:37.570
What are we going to do,
send people back to a country

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:40.120
that they've never been to?

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:44.470
It's insanity.

00:18:48.975 --> 00:18:51.100
MARY SKAFIDAS: Google was
one of the companies that

00:18:51.100 --> 00:18:55.210
