So I want to give
the Googlers a chance

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:24.880
to start asking some questions.

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:27.330
So start thinking of your
questions, and we have mics.

00:21:27.330 --> 00:21:30.070
But just getting
back to the stories,

00:21:30.070 --> 00:21:37.790
I am curious what your
favorite one or ones are.

00:21:37.790 --> 00:21:40.520
And I hope this isn't
like asking you to pick

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:43.780
your favorite child--
probably a little bit--

00:21:43.780 --> 00:21:45.004
and why.

00:21:45.004 --> 00:21:46.170
MARY SKAFIDAS: I have three.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:47.690
JESSE HAINES: And maybe
you could tell the group--

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:48.260
MARY SKAFIDAS: I have three.

00:21:48.260 --> 00:21:50.500
I have three because
I like a lot of them.

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:52.780
But I'm going to pick
three from people

00:21:52.780 --> 00:21:55.460
you probably haven't heard of.

00:21:55.460 --> 00:21:57.680
One is Eric Mezza.

00:21:57.680 --> 00:21:59.210
There's a chapter
in the back that's

00:21:59.210 --> 00:22:03.530
undocumented-- focuses on
undocumented immigrants,

00:22:03.530 --> 00:22:04.700
and my aunt was one of them.

00:22:04.700 --> 00:22:06.680
You know, she took
the job nobody wanted.

00:22:06.680 --> 00:22:08.640
She worked in the
garment industry.

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:14.660
She matched collars to
jackets for pennies a collar.

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:17.985
But she saved a lot
of what she made,

00:22:17.985 --> 00:22:20.360
and she was able to put me
and my cousin through college,

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:21.901
so we have no student
loans, which is

00:22:21.901 --> 00:22:25.490
amazing on what she had made.

00:22:25.490 --> 00:22:26.610
But there's two stories.

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:29.240
One is Juliana Perez.

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:34.460
She had DACA status.

00:22:34.460 --> 00:22:39.830
She just graduated from
Georgetown Law School

00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:42.950
and is now an
immigration lawyer.

00:22:42.950 --> 00:22:46.460
When the book was published,
she had just passed her bar,

00:22:46.460 --> 00:22:48.330
so she was very
excited about that.

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:49.970
And that is a tremendous story.

00:22:49.970 --> 00:22:53.795
Then there's Eric Mezza who is a
junior in Harvard now, I think?

00:22:53.795 --> 00:22:54.920
ANDREW TISCH: No, a senior.

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:56.390
MARY SKAFIDAS:
Senior in Harvard.

00:22:56.390 --> 00:22:58.820
Brilliant, brilliant
mathematical mind.

00:22:58.820 --> 00:23:01.460
But his parents were
migrant workers.

00:23:01.460 --> 00:23:03.920
They would pick oranges in
Florida, then move to Michigan

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:04.880
and back.

00:23:04.880 --> 00:23:09.212
And a nonprofit organization
kind of saw him,

00:23:09.212 --> 00:23:11.420
saw his grades, and was able
to kind of pluck him out

00:23:11.420 --> 00:23:14.270
of the crowd and help
him get to Harvard.

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:17.720
And then the last
one is Ahmed Ahmed.

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:21.530
I think he was born in
a Somali refugee camp.

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:25.850
He moved here when he was
about a couple of years old.

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:27.530
He ended up going to Cornell.

00:23:27.530 --> 00:23:30.245
He's now in Oxford, right?

00:23:30.245 --> 00:23:31.910
A Rhodes scholar.

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:35.450
And it's just the
thing that resonates

00:23:35.450 --> 00:23:40.910
with me is, his parents had a
privileged life where he lived.

00:23:40.910 --> 00:23:44.302
And his mother's now raising
her family basically in tents.

00:23:44.302 --> 00:23:46.010
And when they moved
to the United States,

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:47.030
they had nothing.

00:23:47.030 --> 00:23:49.820
But she views this as
the best day of her life

00:23:49.820 --> 00:23:52.790
because they were able
to start fresh, and not

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:54.530
be worried about men
with machine guns

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:57.450
coming and taking their
family members away.

00:23:57.450 --> 00:24:00.962
So those are the three for me.

00:24:00.962 --> 00:24:02.420
ANDREW TISCH: I
think I'll pick out

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:09.360
two I'll pick Ryan Platt, who
is now a sophomore at Cornell.

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:12.398
And those are the
only two Cornell--

00:24:12.398 --> 00:24:13.850
MARY SKAFIDAS: That's not true.

00:24:13.850 --> 00:24:21.110
ANDREW TISCH: But Ryan is the
daughter of a single mother.

00:24:21.110 --> 00:24:24.230
She's adopted from
a Chinese orphanage.

00:24:24.230 --> 00:24:30.260
And when she went back to China
to see the orphanage from where

00:24:30.260 --> 00:24:34.700
she came, she tells
the story about walking

00:24:34.700 --> 00:24:37.160
into the orphanage
and seeing all

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:44.490
these little Chinese
babies, all girls.

00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:48.230
And she said she had a
very tough time identifying

00:24:48.230 --> 00:24:50.810
with them because
every time she looks

00:24:50.810 --> 00:24:55.050
in the mirror in the morning,
she sees an American girl.

00:24:55.050 --> 00:25:04.280
And it just stuck with me
that her identity is American.

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:10.430
And I guess the other one
is Stephanie Murphy, who

00:25:10.430 --> 00:25:15.291
was a Vietnamese boat
person who left as a--

00:25:15.291 --> 00:25:16.790
MARY SKAFIDAS: Which
you got to love

00:25:16.790 --> 00:25:18.482
with a last name
like Murphy, right?

00:25:18.482 --> 00:25:21.260
JESSE HAINES: I know, I'm like--

00:25:21.260 --> 00:25:24.230
ANDREW TISCH: And
her family left

00:25:24.230 --> 00:25:27.500
Vietnam when it was taken over.

00:25:27.500 --> 00:25:32.690
And they got marooned
on the South China Sea.

00:25:32.690 --> 00:25:35.810
The engine broke down,
and they were adrift,

00:25:35.810 --> 00:25:39.130
and they got picked
up by the US Navy,

00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:43.100
refuelled, fixed the engine,
pointed them towards Malaysia.

00:25:43.100 --> 00:25:50.540
And Stephanie is, today, a
Congresswoman from Orlando.

00:25:50.540 --> 00:25:54.230
So those are the
ones that I like.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:26:02.540
I love Angela Buchwald, who's
a Korean-born rabbi at Central

00:26:02.540 --> 00:26:04.460
Synagogue.

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:08.660
Cory Booker's essay is great.

00:26:08.660 --> 00:26:13.910
Every one of them has
something in there

00:26:13.910 --> 00:26:16.670
that people will
find interesting.

00:26:16.670 --> 00:26:20.590
And some are more
interesting than others.

00:26:20.590 --> 00:26:27.770
I love Pete Gogolak's Pete
Gogolak was a football player.

00:26:27.770 --> 00:26:30.020
They came over from Hungary.

00:26:30.020 --> 00:26:32.730
And he changed the
world twice, actually,

00:26:32.730 --> 00:26:36.900
because he and his brother
couldn't figure out

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:40.050
how to kick a football.

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:41.596
They kicked it
sideways, not forward.

00:26:41.596 --> 00:26:42.720
JESSE HAINES: Soccer-style.

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:46.530
ANDREW TISCH: And became the
first soccer-style kickers.

00:26:46.530 --> 00:26:52.560
And then Pete was drafted by the
New York Giants and the Buffalo

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:56.640
Bills, and started kicking
for the Buffalo Bills.

00:26:56.640 --> 00:27:01.230
And the New York
Giants hired him away

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:04.500
for a bonus of $90,000.

00:27:04.500 --> 00:27:08.580
And the uproar was so great
that it led to the merger talks

00:27:08.580 --> 00:27:12.630
between the American
Football League and the NFL.

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:14.631
So he changed the word twice.

00:27:14.631 --> 00:27:17.130
The way we kick the football,
and the way we watch football.

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:18.463
JESSE HAINES: I love that story.

00:27:18.463 --> 00:27:20.790
I love that story.

00:27:20.790 --> 00:27:22.270
There are so many good ones.

00:27:22.270 --> 00:27:22.770
OK.

