It's huge.

00:42:08.572 --> 00:42:09.280
JESSE HAINES: OK.

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:12.380
ANDREW TISCH: There were
67 new immigrants who

00:42:12.380 --> 00:42:15.650
were sworn in as new citizens.

00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:16.610
And there were, what--

00:42:16.610 --> 00:42:17.485
MARY SKAFIDAS: 3,000.

00:42:17.485 --> 00:42:18.810
ANDREW TISCH: --3,000
people were there?

00:42:18.810 --> 00:42:19.930
MARY SKAFIDAS: Yeah.

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:21.011
It's hot.

00:42:21.011 --> 00:42:21.760
Bring an umbrella.

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:23.970
But it was a
wonderful experience.

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:25.990
And like Andrew
was saying, if this

00:42:25.990 --> 00:42:28.720
was a requirement for
elected officials,

00:42:28.720 --> 00:42:30.490
it would help change
the conversation.

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:31.894
I think he's right.

00:42:31.894 --> 00:42:33.310
AUDIENCE: Someone
asked a question

00:42:33.310 --> 00:42:38.020
about New York City and state
having many social programs

00:42:38.020 --> 00:42:42.940
to help immigrants, and also
you can get free legal advice,

00:42:42.940 --> 00:42:44.330
and so on.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:46.610
And I was actually
wondering, is it

00:42:46.610 --> 00:42:49.180
all in New York City and
state who's doing it?

00:42:49.180 --> 00:42:52.240
Or were more states
in the United States

00:42:52.240 --> 00:42:56.690
who are also involved in
doing programs like that?

00:42:56.690 --> 00:42:59.120
MARY SKAFIDAS: Well, just
from the stories in the book,

00:42:59.120 --> 00:43:01.160
Ahmed Ahmed--

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:03.230
his family was sent to Michigan.

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:06.290
And they had built-in programs.

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:09.227
I don't know if it was provided
by the city or the state.

00:43:09.227 --> 00:43:11.060
It could have been a
nonprofit organization.

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:12.830
But they helped them
find an apartment.

00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:14.480
They helped his
parents find a job.

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:16.700
They helped them
register for school.

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:20.750
I think more urban settings
are probably easier,

00:43:20.750 --> 00:43:24.410
but there is Columbus,
Ohio, for instance.

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:28.250
Actually, their mayor says,
we are open to immigrants

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:30.200
because they need them.

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:33.170
They have plants there that
they can't find enough employees

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:35.990
for, so he was covered
in New York Magazine,

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:38.600
just maybe a year
ago, for setting up

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:45.680
this very pro-immigrant
city that attracted.

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:47.180
And he actually
would raise his hand

00:43:47.180 --> 00:43:50.390
and say, yes, I would like how
ever many new immigrants are

00:43:50.390 --> 00:43:52.090
coming over this month.

00:43:52.090 --> 00:43:54.110
And they worked at
the sausage factory.

00:43:54.110 --> 00:43:56.840
There were different other
factories and plants there.

00:43:56.840 --> 00:43:59.390
But it's one of the
things that helped

00:43:59.390 --> 00:44:03.422
their economy recover faster
than other parts of Ohio.

00:44:03.422 --> 00:44:04.130
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:44:04.130 --> 00:44:05.000
MARY SKAFIDAS: Yeah.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.520
My cousin, actually,
is an American citizen.

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:10.520
He lived for Greece
for a number of years.

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:14.480
He's a mechanical engineer
and he just moved back here

00:44:14.480 --> 00:44:17.000
a year ago.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:19.480
And there were great
systems in place.

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:21.580
He's a citizen, but his
wife and his son aren't.

00:44:21.580 --> 00:44:23.780
There are great
systems in place,

00:44:23.780 --> 00:44:26.720
free of charge in New York,
that helped him kind of settle

00:44:26.720 --> 00:44:28.389
his family and assimilate.

00:44:28.389 --> 00:44:30.680
And the amazing thing is--
he's a mechanical engineer--

00:44:30.680 --> 00:44:35.260
so within three weeks,
he had three job offers.

00:44:35.260 --> 00:44:36.940
AUDIENCE: Are your
stories in this book?

00:44:36.940 --> 00:44:43.863
And how did they influence the
way you approached this book?

00:44:43.863 --> 00:44:45.910
MARY SKAFIDAS: Well, his
story started it all.

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:47.165
It was the research.

00:44:47.165 --> 00:44:48.380
Go ahead.

00:44:48.380 --> 00:44:49.130
ANDREW TISCH: Yes.

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:51.110
Yes, indeed, our
stories are in the book.

00:44:51.110 --> 00:44:55.340
And when we send out
the request to people,

00:44:55.340 --> 00:45:00.170
we led with our chins in that
we sent our stories to them

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:03.920
to say, we're willing to
put our stories in the book.

00:45:03.920 --> 00:45:06.390
We hope that you will join us.

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:14.960
And we had very few turndowns
from people because they were

00:45:14.960 --> 00:45:16.290
excited to be part of this.

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:20.390
And one of the things
you'll find in the book

00:45:20.390 --> 00:45:26.930
is that the last
eight pages are blank.

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:29.450
And they're just lined
so that you can write

00:45:29.450 --> 00:45:31.820
your story into your book.

00:45:31.820 --> 00:45:33.770
We also give you the
opportunity to go

00:45:33.770 --> 00:45:38.780
to
www.journeysanamericanstory.com,

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:44.470
and put your story
onto our website,

00:45:44.470 --> 00:45:46.700
so that there are
additional stories

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:51.860
on the website of people
whose stories came in too

00:45:51.860 --> 00:45:54.260
late to make publication.

00:45:54.260 --> 00:45:59.660
So we're anxious that
people tell the stories

00:45:59.660 --> 00:46:05.070
because the more
they talk about it,

00:46:05.070 --> 00:46:11.120
the more we believe
people will remember

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:16.070
that we are all, as Americans,
from somewhere else.

00:46:16.070 --> 00:46:20.372
But we're here as Americans,
and we're here together

00:46:20.372 --> 00:46:22.830
JESSE HAINES: I think that's
a really great note to end on.

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:24.220
Thank you again for being here.

00:46:24.220 --> 00:46:26.790
Thank you for creating this
book, for sharing your stories,

00:46:26.790 --> 00:46:29.320
for sharing the stories
of so many others.

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:32.280
And I hope you guys will
share your stories, maybe

00:46:32.280 --> 00:46:35.160
by hand, maybe on the website.

00:46:35.160 --> 00:46:36.900
And thank you for
being here today.

00:46:36.900 --> 00:46:37.300
MARY SKAFIDAS: Thank you.

